window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2016>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2016","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"You are provided with a uniform metre rule, a knife-edge, some masses and other necessary materials.  (i) Determine and record the centre of gravity of the metre rule.  (ii) Fix the 100 g mass marked  N at a point Y, the 80 cm mark of the rule using a sellotape.  (iii) Suspend another 50 g mass marked  M at X, a distance  A = 10 cm  from the 0 cm mark of the rule.  (iv) Balance the arrangement horizontally on the knife edge as illustrated in the diagram above.  (v) Measure and record the distance  B of a knife-edge from the 0 cm mark of the rule.  (vi) Repeat the procedure for four other values of  A  = 15 cm, 20 cm, 25cm and 30cm.   (vii) Tabulate your readings.  (viii) Plot a graph with  B on the vertical axis and  A on the horizontal axis.  (ix) Determine the slope,  s , of the graph.  (x) Also determine the intercept,  c , on the vertical axis.  (xi) Evaluate:  (\u03b1) k1 = (1\u22122ss\\frac{1-2s}{s}s1\u22122s\u200b)100  (\u03b2) k2 = (2cs\\frac{2c}{s}s2c\u200b) - 160  (xii) State two precautions taken to obtain accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/N A(cm) B(cm)1 10.0 52.52 15.0 54.33 20.0 55.34 25.0 56.25 30.0 57.2        (ix) s = \u2206B\u2206A\\frac{\u2206B}{\u2206A}\u2206A\u2206B\u200b = B2\u2212B1A2\u2212A1\\frac{B_{2}-B_{1}}{A_{2}-A_{1}}A2\u200b\u2212A1\u200bB2\u200b\u2212B1\u200b\u200b = 57.2\u221252.530\u221210\\frac{57.2-52.5}{30-10}30\u22121057.2\u221252.5\u200b = 4.720\\frac{4.7}{20}204.7\u200b = 0.24    (x) c = 50.6    (xi)     (\u03b1) k1 = 1\u22122ss\\frac{1-2s}{s}s1\u22122s\u200b \u00d7 100 = 1\u22122\u00d70.240.24\\frac{1-2\u00d70.24}{0.24}0.241\u22122\u00d70.24\u200b \u00d7 100 = 1\u22120.480.24\\frac{1-0.48}{0.24}0.241\u22120.48\u200b \u00d7 100 = 0.520.24\\frac{0.52}{0.24}0.240.52\u200b \u00d7 100 = 136\\frac{13}{6}613\u200b \u00d7 100 = 216.67    (\u03b2) k2 = 2cs\\frac{2c}{s}s2c\u200b - 160 = 2\u00d750.60.24\\frac{2\u00d750.6}{0.24}0.242\u00d750.6\u200b - 160 = 101.20.24\\frac{101.2}{0.24}0.24101.2\u200b - 160 = 421.67 - 160 = 261.67     Precautions:   1. I ensured the experiment was conducted in a location free of draughts to prevent external forces from affecting the setup.    2. I ensured the mass was suspended freely and did not touch or rest on the table to guarantee accurate force measurements.    3. I ensured I avoided parallax errors by positioning my eyes directly perpendicular to the scale of the metre rule while taking readings.    4. I ensured repeated readings were taken to minimize random errors and improve the reliability of the results.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2016>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2016","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : PRINCIPLE OF MOMENTS","question":"Define the moment of a force about a point.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The moment of a force about a point is the measure of the tendency of the force to cause rotational motion around that point. It is defined as the product of the force and the perpendicular distance from the point to the line of action of the force. Mathematically, it is expressed as:    Moment = Force \u00d7 Perpendicular\u00a0Distance    where the perpendicular distance is the shortest distance from the point to the force's line of action. The moment's direction is determined using the right-hand rule or by the convention of clockwise and anticlockwise moments.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2016>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2016","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"State two conditions under which a rigid body at rest remains in equilibrium when acted upon by non-parallel coplanar forces.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"1. The vector sum of all forces must be zero, ensuring no net force in any direction.    2. The algebraic sum of the moments about any point must be zero, preventing rotation.    3. The forces must be concurrent, meeting or intersecting at a common point.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2016>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2016","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : EVAPORATION AND BOILING","question":"You are provided with a beaker, a thermometer, a stirrer, a measuring cylinder, a bunsen burner, a wire gauze, a 50 g mass, a pair of tongs, water, tripod stand, and other necessary materials.  (i) Using the measuring cylinder, measure 150 cm3 of water into the beaker.  (ii) Record the volume, V of the water in the beaker  (iii) Calculate the mass m of the water, given that  m  = \u03c1v and \u03c1 = 1 gcm-3.   (iv) Measure and record the initial temperature \u03b80 of the water in the beaker.  (v) Hold the 50 g mass with the pair of tongs in the flame of the bunsen burner for 2 minutes.   (vi) Quickly transfer the 50 g mass to water in the beaker.  (vii) Stir gently and record the highest temperature \u03b81, attained   (viii) Evaluate  \u03b8 = (\u03b81 - \u03b80)   (ix) Empty the content of the beaker and repeat the procedures above for the values of  V  = 200 cm3 , 250 cm3, 300 cm3, and 350 cm3.  (x) Tabulate your readings.  (xi) Plot a graph with  m on the vertical axis and  \u03b8 on the horizontal axis.  (xii) Determine the slope,  s , of the graph.  (xiii) Evaluate k =  50s\\frac{50}{s}s50\u200b.  (xiv) State two precautions taken to obtain accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"\u03b80 = 29\u00b0C    S/N  V(cm3) m(g) \u03b8 = (\u03b81 - \u03b80)\u00b0C 1 150 150.0102 200 200.0 83 250 250.064 300 300.045 350 350.0 2    Initial temperature of water = 34\u00b0 c    (xii) s = \u2206m\u2206\u03b8\\frac{\u2206m}{\u2206\u03b8}\u2206\u03b8\u2206m\u200b = m2\u2212m1\u03b82\u2212\u03b81\\frac{m_{2}-m_{1}}{\u03b8_{2}-\u03b8_{1}}\u03b82\u200b\u2212\u03b81\u200bm2\u200b\u2212m1\u200b\u200b = 150\u221235010\u22122\\frac{150-350}{10-2}10\u22122150\u2212350\u200b = \u22122008\\frac{-200}{8}8\u2212200\u200b = -25    (xiii) k = 50s\\frac{50}{s}s50\u200b = 50\u221225\\frac{50}{-25}\u22122550\u200b = -2      Precautions;     1. I ensured water splashing was avoided to maintain accuracy and safety during the experiment.    2. I stirred the water continuously to ensure even distribution of heat throughout the mixture.    3. I avoided parallax errors by positioning my eyes level with the scale on the thermometer and measuring cylinder while taking readings.    4. I took repeated readings and recorded them in a table to improve reliability and accuracy.    5. I ensured the heated mass was gently lowered into the beaker to prevent splashing and minimize heat loss.    6. I ensured the beaker was stable and free from external disturbances during the experiment.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2016>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2016","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : HEAT CAPACITY","question":"Define heat capacity.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Heat capacity is the amount of heat energy required to raise the temperature of a substance by one degree Celsius (or one kelvin). It is a measure of the thermal energy a substance can absorb or release for a given temperature change. Mathematically, it is expressed as:    C = H\u0394T\\frac{H}{\u0394T}\u0394TH\u200b  \u200b  where:  C is the heat capacity,  H is the heat energy absorbed or released,  \u0394T is the change in temperature.    Heat capacity is measured in joules per degree Celsius (J/\u00b0C) or joules per kelvin (J/K).","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2016>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2016","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : SPECIFIC HEAT CAPACITY","question":"An electric kettle rated 1.2 kW is used to heat 800 g of water initially at a temperature of 20oC. Neglecting heat losses, calculate the time taken for the kettle to heat the water to its boiling point. [Take the boiling point of water = 100oC, specific heat capacity of water = 4200 Jkg-1K-1]    (Provide your answer with the unit e.g 5 m)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Pt = mc\u0394\u03b8    1200t = 8001000\\frac{800}{1000}1000800\u200b \u00d7 4200 \u00d7 (100 - 20)    1200t = 0.8 \u00d7 4200 \u00d7 80    1200t = 268800    t = 2688001200\\frac{268800}{1200}1200268800\u200b = 224 s","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2016>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2016","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"You are provided with a variable d.c. power supply E, a 2 \u03a9 standard resistor, a key, an ammeter, a voltmeter and other necessary materials.  (i) Set up a circuit as shown in the diagram above with  E  = 1.5 V  (ii) Close the key k.  (iii) Take and record the voltmeter reading  V .  (iv) Take and record the corresponding ammeter reading  l .  (v) Evaluate  V-1 \t and  l-1 \t    (vi) Repeat the procedure for four other values of  E  = 3.0 V, 4.5 V, 6.0 V, and 7.4 V.  (vii) Tabulate your readings.  (viii) Plot a graph with  V-1  on the vertical axis and  l-1 on the horizontal axis starting both axes from the origin (0, 0).   (ix) Determine the slope,  s , of the graph.  (x) Also determine the intercept,  c , on the vertical axis.   (xi) State two precautions taken to obtain accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/N E(V) I(A) V(V)  V-1(V-1) l -1(A-1)1 1.5 0.30 0.80 1.250 3.3332 3.0 0.50 0.40 0.717 2.0003 4.5 0.70 2.00 0.500 1.4294 6.0 0.90 2.50 0.400 1.1115 7.5 1.10 3.00 0.333 0.909        (ix) s = \u2206V\u22121\u2206I\u22121\\frac{\u2206V^{-1}}{\u2206I^{-1}}\u2206I\u22121\u2206V\u22121\u200b = V2\u22121\u2212V1\u22121I2\u22121\u2212I1\u22121\\frac{V^{-1}_{2}-V^{-1}_{1}}{I^{-1}_{2}-I^{-1}_{1}}I2\u22121\u200b\u2212I1\u22121\u200bV2\u22121\u200b\u2212V1\u22121\u200b\u200b = 1.25\u22120.3333.333\u22120.909\\frac{1.25-0.333}{3.333-0.909}3.333\u22120.9091.25\u22120.333\u200b = 0.9172.424\\frac{0.917}{2.424}2.4240.917\u200b = 0.38    (x) c = 0.029     Precaution:     1. I ensured the terminals and connections were clean and tight to prevent inaccurate readings due to poor contact.    2. I ensured the key was also removed when readings were not being taken, further preventing errors.    3. I avoided parallax errors on the voltmeter and ammeter by positioning my eyes directly perpendicular to the scale while taking measurements.    4. I noted and corrected any zero error in the voltmeter and ammeter before starting the experiment to ensure accurate readings.    5. I repeated the readings to minimize random errors and improve the reliability of the data collected.    6. I ensured that the instruments were calibrated properly before use to avoid systematic errors.    7. I checked all connections for any signs of loose wiring before starting each measurement cycle to prevent fluctuating readings.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2016>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2016","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : PRODUCTION OF ELECTRIC CURRENT","question":"State two methods by which an electric current can be produced.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Electric current can be produced through various methods, including:    1. Chemical Methods: Cells (such as accumulators and fuel cells) generate current through chemical reactions, converting chemical energy into electrical energy.    2. Mechanical Methods: Generators and dynamos use electromagnetic induction, where motion within a magnetic field induces current (used in power plants and mechanical systems).    3. Solar Energy: Solar cells (photocells) convert light energy directly into electricity via the photovoltaic effect.    4. Heat Energy: Thermocouples and thermopiles generate current through the Seebeck effect (temperature differences). Thermionic generators and geothermal sources also convert heat to electricity.    5. Mechanical Movement: Windmills, tidal waves, hydro power, and gas turbines harness mechanical energy from nature to produce electricity.    6. Nuclear Energy: Nuclear power plants use nuclear reactions to generate heat, which is then converted into electricity.    7. Electrostatic Methods: Electrostatic generators, such as the Van de Graff generator, produce electricity through static charge accumulation.    8. Piezoelectric Effect: Piezoelectric generators generate current when mechanical stress is applied to certain materials like quartz.    These methods span across different sources of energy, including chemical, mechanical, thermal, solar, and nuclear, offering diverse approaches to electricity generation","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2016>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2016","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"Calculate the value of R in the circuit diagram shown above, given that the effective resistance of the circuit is 4.0 \u03a9 and the internal resistance of the cell is negligible.    (Provide your answer without the unit)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"1Rpar\\frac{1}{R_{par}}Rpar\u200b1\u200b = 1R\\frac{1}{R}R1\u200b + 1R\\frac{1}{R}R1\u200b    1Rpar\\frac{1}{R_{par}}Rpar\u200b1\u200b = 1R\\frac{1}{R}R1\u200b + 1R\\frac{1}{R}R1\u200b    1Rpar\\frac{1}{R_{par}}Rpar\u200b1\u200b = 2R\\frac{2}{R}R2\u200b    Rpar = R2\\frac{R}{2}2R\u200b    RT = Rpar + 2    4 = R2\\frac{R}{2}2R\u200b + 2    R2\\frac{R}{2}2R\u200b = 4 - 2    R2\\frac{R}{2}2R\u200b = 2    R = 2 \u00d7 2    \u2234 R = 4 \u03a9","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];